Here is a super simplified example of a PHP app that in my opinion should never divulge the contents of the php process stack, regardless what parameters you put to the form fields. Yet, it can be coaxed to do that by manipulating the env parameters as described in this ticket.

```
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>libcurl telnet test</title>
</head>

<body>

<?php

if (isset($_POST['server']) && isset($_POST['env']))
{
  $server = $_POST['server'];
  if (filter_var($server, FILTER_VALIDATE_IP))
  {
    $env = array();
    foreach($_POST['env'] as $key => $value) {
      $env[] = 'NEW_ENV=' . $value;
    }

    $ch = curl_init('telnet://' . $server);
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_TELNETOPTIONS, $env);
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_TIMEOUT, 2);
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, TRUE);
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST, 'foo');
    $output=curl_exec($ch);
    curl_close($ch);
  }
}

?>

<form method="POST">
  <label for="">telnet server:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="server" name="server" value="127.0.0.1"><br>
  <label for="">env:</label><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[0]" value="foo,bar" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[1]" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[2]" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[4]" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[5]" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[6]" /><br>
  <input type="text" name="env[7]" /><br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

</body>
</html>
```
